<font color="#FF0000">TO COOK, SW AND ED</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct 16  4:34:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
My message to you was not meant to show you as a fake. If I didn't think you were worth the effort, I would not be here. You, as well as I, need reminding on occasion. Members of your church, if they truly love each other, hold each other accountable.<br><br>
From the beginning I have said that I respect your opinions.<br>
That has not changed.<br><br>
The whole notion of Vietnam veterans exercising payback by spitting on people 30 years after the fact shows a determination, in my opinion, for retribution. As a Vietnam vet, I refuse to accept this notion, and strongly feel that modern day vets sanctioning such only reinforces the stereotype that people have of Us - the vet.<br><br>
There is no excuse for spitting.<br><br>
I believe it was the prophet Isaiah who said that we (meaning us) are all filthy rags. I don't wear a robe, was never called to. I don't consider myself holy, only a sinner in need of mercy.<br><br>
Ed,<br><br>
I understand the anger that any would feel when being spit upon. I have been spit on. See my response to SW.<br><br>
SW<br><br>
In a post of yours the other day you said that you would do much worse than &quot;spitting&quot; if someone had ever spit on you. I can't imagine anything worse than spitting. Really.<br><br>
When I was 8 years old a kid about 12 or 13 spit in my face. Since then I have vague memories of the numerous ass kickings that I have received as a kid. Vague memories. The spitting I remember as if it were yesterday. I can't ever forget the sense of shame I felt at the time - as if I had done something wrong.<br><br>
There was no excuse for anyone spitting on returning soldiers, this is certain. But my feelings are that we, as middle aged men, only make ourselves into our adversary when we engage in deplorable conduct.<br><br>
What would I have done had I been faced with a spitting situation in an airport? I can't say for sure. However, my sense of having answered the call and done my duty most likely would have allowed me to walk past any jeering or spitting people, giving them as little notice as possible.<br><br>
I still am very proud of my service in Vietnam. Nothing anything can do or say and no amount of disrespect or spittle can diminish it. To be like an adversary by sinking to the depths of spitting could not in any way enhance that service, either.<br><br>
Nothing said here requires an apology, I agree with Ed.<br><br>
I feel very strongly about this issue, I can say that. Just look at the time that this message is posted.<br><br>
Peace to All.
<p><code>-- wingman#greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


